    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-04-06T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-04-06T12:00:00-05:00" n="182"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d182">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">860F.4061 Motion Pictures/126: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Czechoslovakia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Carr</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Praha</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-04-06T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 6, 1938—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 6—1:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>56. From Culbertson. It was not until yesterday that we made any progress on the
                    motion picture question. On my arrival here I found the situation even more
                    complicated than we had thought in Washington. We prepared a list of 14 points
                    which was presented to the Czechs. They have met us partially or wholly on 12
                    points <pb facs="0240" n="232" xml:id="pg_232"/> and I feel we can probably come
                    to an acceptable agreement within the fairly near future. The most important
                    outstanding is the registration fee of 20,000 crowns. While they have offered no
                    reduction in this amount they have suggested it be imposed as an import license
                    tax and payable to the Ministry of Commerce. No doubt the money will still find
                    its way into the hands of the domestic industry as a governmental subsidy but so
                    long as our industry is not required to pay it into the hands of the domestic
                    industry I feel we have made our point on the principle involved. There is
                    really no chance of getting this fee abolished but I am in hopes we can get it
                    reduced. Refusal of our requests has been based on political considerations
                    which the Czechs feel are real and pressing. Some of our requests are without
                    doubt difficult for them. [Culbertson.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Carr</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
